# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gguf-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] A **binary file** is a computer file that is not a text file.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The term "binary file" is often used as a term meaning "non-text file".
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Many binary file formats contain parts that can be interpreted as text; for example, some computer document files containing formatted text, such as older Microsoft Word document files, contain the text of the document but also contain formatting information in binary form.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] All modern computers store information in the form of bits (binary digits), using binary code.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For this reason, all data stored on a computer is, in some sense, "binary".
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] However, one particularly useful and ubiquitous type of data stored on a computer is one in which the bits represent text, by way of a character encoding.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Those files are called "text files" and files which are not like that are referred to as "binary files", as a sort of retronym or hypernym.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] These mixed binary-and-text file are usually regarded as "binary", because an application that can only process text will not know what to do with them.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For example, in a binary file, the number 250 could be encoded in bits as the sequence 11111010.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] It could also be encoded in a text file (for example, a programming language source file) as the digits 2, 5, 0; which would in turn be encoded by the bits in the text file as (for example, using UTF-8) 00110010, 00110101, 00110000.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Binary files are usually thought of as being a sequence of bytes, which means the binary digits (bits) are grouped in eights.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Binary files typically contain bytes that are intended to be interpreted as something other than text characters.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Compiled computer programs are typical examples; indeed, compiled applications are sometimes referred to, particularly by programmers, as **binaries**.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] But binary files can also mean that they contain images, sounds, compressed versions of other files, etc. – in short, any type of file content whatsoever.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Some binary files contain headers, blocks of metadata used by a computer program to interpret the data in the file.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The header often contains a signature or *magic* number which can identify the format.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For example, a GIF file can contain multiple images, and headers are used to identify and describe each block of image data.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The leading bytes of the header would contain text like `GIF87a` or `GIF89a` that can identify the binary as a GIF file.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] If a binary file does not contain any headers, it may be called a **flat binary file**.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] A text file may consist partly or entirely of encoded binary information.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] When sending binary files over the network they may be encoded so that they use only printable characters.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] This is often necessary due to the limitations of network protocols used for internet browsing and e-mail communication.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Also, files containing public-key and private-key information for use in systems employing asymmetric cryptography (such as website certificates) may also be stored with the binary information encoded in printable characters.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] To send binary files through certain systems (such as email) that do not allow all data values, they are often translated into a plain text representation (using, for example, Base64).
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Encoding the data has the disadvantage of increasing the file size during the transfer (for example, using Base64 will increase the file's size by approximately 30%), as well as requiring translation back into binary after receipt.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The increased size may be countered by lower-level link compression, as the resulting text data will have about as much less entropy as it has increased size, so the actual data transferred in this scenario would likely be very close to the size of the original binary data.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] See Binary-to-text encoding for more on this subject.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] In Unix-like systems, the C and C++ standard libraries on those systems also allow the programmer to specify whether a file is expected to be text or binary, but the libraries can and do ignore that parameter, as the end-of-line sequence in Unix-like systems is just the C/C++ end-of-line character.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] A hex editor or viewer may be used to view file data as a sequence of hexadecimal (or decimal, binary or ASCII character) values for corresponding bytes of a binary file.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] If a binary file is opened in a text editor, each group of eight bits will typically be translated as a single character, and the user will see a (probably unintelligible) display of textual characters.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] If the file is opened in some other application, that application will have its own use for each byte: maybe the application will treat each byte as a number and output a stream of numbers between 0 and 255—or maybe interpret the numbers in the bytes as colors and display the corresponding picture.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Other type of viewers (called 'word extractors') simply replace the unprintable characters with spaces revealing only the human-readable text.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] This type of view is useful for a quick inspection of a binary file in order to find passwords in games, find hidden text in non-text files and recover corrupted documents.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] It can even be used to inspect suspicious files (software) for unwanted effects.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For example, the user would see any URL/email to which the suspected software may attempt to connect in order to upload unapproved data (to steal).
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] If the file is itself treated as an executable and run, then the operating system will attempt to interpret the file as a series of instructions in its machine language.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Standards are very important to binary files.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For example, a binary file interpreted by the ASCII character set will result in text being displayed.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] A custom application can interpret the file differently: a byte may be a sound, or a pixel, or even an entire word.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Binary itself is meaningless, until such time as an executed algorithm defines what should be done with each bit, byte, word or block.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Thus, just examining the binary and attempting to match it against known formats can lead to the wrong conclusion as to what it actually represents.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] This fact can be used in steganography, where an algorithm interprets a binary data file differently to reveal hidden content.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Without the algorithm, it is impossible to tell that hidden content exists.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Two files that are binary compatible will have the same sequence of zeros and ones in the data portion of the file.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The file header, however, may be different.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] The term is used most commonly to state that data files produced by one application are exactly the same as data files produced by another application.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] For example, some software companies produce applications for Windows and the Macintosh that are binary compatible, which means that a file produced in a Windows environment is interchangeable with a file produced on a Macintosh.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] This avoids many of the conversion problems caused by importing and exporting data.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] One possible binary compatibility issue between different computers is the endianness of the computer.
[src:gguf-format/binary-file] Some computers store the bytes in a file in a different order.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In information theory, **data compression**, **source coding**, or **bit-rate reduction** is the process of encoding information using fewer bits than the original representation.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Any particular compression is either lossy or lossless.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossless compression reduces bits by identifying and eliminating statistical redundancy.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] No information is lost in lossless compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy compression reduces bits by removing unnecessary or less important information.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Typically, a device that performs data compression is referred to as an encoder, and one that performs the reversal of the process (decompression) as a decoder.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The process of reducing the size of a data file is often referred to as data compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the context of data transmission, it is called source coding: encoding is done at the source of the data before it is stored or transmitted.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Source coding should not be confused with channel coding, for error detection and correction or line coding, the means for mapping data onto a signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Data compression algorithms present a space–time complexity trade-off between the bytes needed to store or transmit information, and the computational resources needed to perform the encoding and decoding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The design of data compression schemes involves balancing the degree of compression, the amount of distortion introduced (when using lossy data compression), and the computational resources or time required to compress and decompress the data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms usually exploit statistical redundancy to represent data without losing any information, so that the process is reversible.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossless compression is possible because most real-world data exhibits statistical redundancy.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For example, an image may have areas of color that do not change over several pixels; instead of coding "red pixel, red pixel, ..." the data may be encoded as "279 red pixels".
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This is a basic example of run-length encoding; there are many schemes to reduce file size by eliminating redundancy.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The Lempel–Ziv (LZ) compression methods are among the most popular algorithms for lossless storage.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] DEFLATE is a variation on LZ optimized for decompression speed and compression ratio, but compression can be slow.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the mid-1980s, following work by Terry Welch, the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) algorithm rapidly became the method of choice for most general-purpose compression systems.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] LZW is used in GIF images, programs such as PKZIP, and hardware devices such as modems.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] LZ methods use a table-based compression model where table entries are substituted for repeated strings of data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For most LZ methods, this table is generated dynamically from earlier data in the input.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The table itself is often Huffman encoded.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Grammar-based codes like this can compress highly repetitive input extremely effectively, for instance, a biological data collection of the same or closely related species, a huge versioned document collection, internet archival, etc.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The basic task of grammar-based codes is constructing a context-free grammar deriving a single string.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Other practical grammar compression algorithms include Sequitur and Re-Pair.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The strongest modern lossless compressors use probabilistic models, such as prediction by partial matching.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The Burrows–Wheeler transform can also be viewed as an indirect form of statistical modelling.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In a further refinement of the direct use of probabilistic modelling, statistical estimates can be coupled to an algorithm called arithmetic coding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding is a more modern coding technique that uses the mathematical calculations of a finite-state machine to produce a string of encoded bits from a series of input data symbols.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It can achieve superior compression compared to other techniques, such as the better-known Huffman algorithm.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It uses an internal memory state to avoid the need to perform a one-to-one mapping of individual input symbols to distinct representations that use an integer number of bits, and it clears out the internal memory only after encoding the entire string of data symbols.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding applies especially well to adaptive data compression tasks where the statistics vary and are context-dependent, as it can be easily coupled with an adaptive model of the probability distribution of the input data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] An early example of the use of arithmetic coding was in an optional (but not widely used) feature of the JPEG image coding standard.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It has since been applied in various other designs including H.263, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC for video coding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Archive software typically has the ability to adjust the "dictionary size", where a larger size demands more random-access memory during compression and decompression, but compresses more strongly, especially on repeating patterns in files' content.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the late 1980s, digital images became more common, and standards for lossless image compression emerged.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the early 1990s, lossy compression methods began to be widely used.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In these schemes, some loss of information is accepted as dropping nonessential detail can save storage space.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] There is a corresponding trade-off between preserving information and reducing size.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy data compression schemes are designed based on research on how people perceive the data in question.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For example, the human eye is more sensitive to subtle variations in luminance than it is to the variations in color.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] JPEG image compression works in part by rounding off nonessential bits of information.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] A number of popular compression formats exploit these perceptual differences, including psychoacoustics for sound, and psychovisuals for images and video.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Most forms of lossy compression are based on transform coding, especially the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It was first proposed in 1972 by Nasir Ahmed, who then developed a working algorithm with T.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Rao in 1973, before introducing it in January 1974.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] DCT is the most widely used lossy compression method, and is used in multimedia formats for images (such as JPEG and HEIF), video (such as MPEG, AVC and HEVC) and audio (such as MP3, AAC and Vorbis).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy image compression is used in digital cameras, to increase storage capacities.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Similarly, DVDs, Blu-ray and streaming video use lossy video coding formats.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy compression is extensively used in video.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In lossy audio compression, methods of psychoacoustics are used to remove non-audible (or less audible) components of the audio signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Compression of human speech is often performed with even more specialized techniques; speech coding is distinguished as a separate discipline from general-purpose audio compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Speech coding is used in internet telephony, for example, audio compression is used for CD ripping and is decoded by the audio players.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy compression can cause generation loss.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The theoretical basis for compression is provided by information theory and, more specifically, Shannon's source coding theorem; domain-specific theories include algorithmic information theory for lossless compression and rate–distortion theory for lossy compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] These areas of study were essentially created by Claude Shannon, who published fundamental papers on the topic in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Other topics associated with compression include coding theory and statistical inference.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Data compression can be viewed as a special case of data differencing.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This is the same as considering absolute entropy (corresponding to data compression) as a special case of relative entropy (corresponding to data differencing) with no initial data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The term *differential compression* is used to emphasize the data differencing connection.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Entropy coding originated in the 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was developed in 1950.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] An important image compression technique is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a technique developed in the early 1970s.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] DCT is the basis for JPEG, a lossy compression format which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] JPEG greatly reduces the amount of data required to represent an image at the cost of a relatively small reduction in image quality and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Its highly efficient DCT-based compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed in 1984.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression, the use of wavelets in image compression, began after the development of DCT coding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was introduced in 2000.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Audio data compression, not to be confused with dynamic range compression, has the potential to reduce the transmission bandwidth and storage requirements of audio data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Audio compression formats compression algorithms are implemented in software as audio codecs.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In both lossy and lossless compression, information redundancy is reduced, using methods such as coding, quantization, DCT and linear prediction to reduce the amount of information used to represent the uncompressed data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression algorithms provide higher compression and are used in numerous audio applications including Vorbis and MP3.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] These algorithms almost all rely on psychoacoustics to eliminate or reduce fidelity of less audible sounds, thereby reducing the space required to store or transmit them.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The acceptable trade-off between loss of audio quality and transmission or storage size depends upon the application.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For example, one 640 MB compact disc (CD) holds approximately one hour of uncompressed high fidelity music, less than 2 hours of music compressed losslessly, or 7 hours of music compressed in the MP3 format at a medium bit rate.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] A digital sound recorder can typically store around 200 hours of clearly intelligible speech in 640 MB.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossless audio compression produces a representation of digital data that can be decoded to an exact digital duplicate of the original.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Compression ratios are around 50–60% of the original size, which is similar to those for generic lossless data compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossless codecs use curve fitting or linear prediction as a basis for estimating the signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Parameters describing the estimation and the difference between the estimation and the actual signal are coded separately.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] A number of lossless audio compression formats exist.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] See list of lossless codecs for a listing.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Some formats are associated with a distinct system, such as Direct Stream Transfer, used in Super Audio CD and Meridian Lossless Packing, used in DVD-Audio, Dolby TrueHD, Blu-ray and HD DVD.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Some audio file formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction; this allows stripping the correction to easily obtain a lossy file.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, and OptimFROG DualStream.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] When audio files are to be processed, either by further compression or for editing, it is desirable to work from an unchanged original (uncompressed or losslessly compressed).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Processing of a lossily compressed file for some purpose usually produces a final result inferior to the creation of the same compressed file from an uncompressed original.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In addition to sound editing or mixing, lossless audio compression is often used for archival storage, or as master copies.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression is used in a wide range of applications.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In addition to standalone audio-only applications of file playback in MP3 players or computers, digitally compressed audio streams are used in most video DVDs, digital television, streaming media on the Internet, satellite and cable radio, and increasingly in terrestrial radio broadcasts.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy compression typically achieves far greater compression than lossless compression, by discarding less-critical data based on psychoacoustic optimizations.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Psychoacoustics recognizes that not all data in an audio stream can be perceived by the human auditory system.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Most lossy compression reduces redundancy by first identifying perceptually irrelevant sounds, that is, sounds that are very hard to hear.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Typical examples include high frequencies or sounds that occur at the same time as louder sounds.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Those irrelevant sounds are coded with decreased accuracy or not at all.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Due to the nature of lossy algorithms, audio quality suffers a digital generation loss when a file is decompressed and recompressed.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This makes lossy compression unsuitable for storing the intermediate results in professional audio engineering applications, such as sound editing and multitrack recording.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] However, lossy formats such as MP3 are very popular with end-users as the file size is reduced to 5-20% of the original size and a megabyte can store about a minute's worth of music at adequate quality.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Several proprietary lossy compression algorithms have been developed that provide higher quality audio performance by using a combination of lossless and lossy algorithms with adaptive bit rates and lower compression ratios.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Examples include aptX, LDAC, LHDC, MQA and SCL6.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] To determine what information in an audio signal is perceptually irrelevant, most lossy compression algorithms use transforms such as the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) to convert time domain sampled waveforms into a transform domain, typically the frequency domain.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Once transformed, component frequencies can be prioritized according to how audible they are.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Equal-loudness contours may also be used to weigh the perceptual importance of components.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Models of the human ear-brain combination incorporating such effects are often called psychoacoustic models.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Other types of lossy compressors, such as the linear predictive coding (LPC) used with speech, are source-based coders.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] LPC uses a model of the human vocal tract to analyze speech sounds and infer the parameters used by the model to produce them moment to moment.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] These changing parameters are transmitted or stored and used to drive another model in the decoder, which reproduces the sound.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Lossy formats are often used for the distribution of streaming audio or interactive communication (such as in cell phone networks).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In such applications, the data must be decompressed as the data flows, rather than after the entire data stream has been transmitted.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Not all audio codecs can be used for streaming applications.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Latency is introduced by the methods used to encode and decode the data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Some codecs will analyze a longer segment, called a *frame*, of the data to optimize efficiency, and then code it in a manner that requires a larger segment of data at one time to decode.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The inherent latency of the coding algorithm can be critical; for example, when there is a two-way transmission of data, such as with a telephone conversation, significant delays may seriously degrade the perceived quality.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In contrast to the speed of compression, which is proportional to the number of operations required by the algorithm, here latency refers to the number of samples that must be analyzed before a block of audio is processed.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the minimum case, latency is zero samples (e.g., if the coder/decoder simply reduces the number of bits used to quantize the signal).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Time domain algorithms such as LPC also often have low latencies, hence their popularity in speech coding for telephony.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In algorithms such as MP3, however, a large number of samples have to be analyzed to implement a psychoacoustic model in the frequency domain, and latency is on the order of 23 ms.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Speech encoding is an important category of audio data compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The perceptual models used to estimate what aspects of speech a human ear can hear are generally somewhat different from those used for music.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The range of frequencies needed to convey the sounds of a human voice is normally far narrower than that needed for music, and the sound is normally less complex.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] As a result, speech can be encoded at high quality using a relatively low bit rate.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The earliest algorithms used in speech encoding (and audio data compression in general) were the A-law algorithm and the μ-law algorithm.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Early audio research was conducted at Bell Labs.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Chapin Cutler filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In 1973, Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding is used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3 and AAC.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Discrete cosine transform (DCT), developed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Rao in 1974, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3, Dolby Digital, and AAC.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The world's first commercial broadcast automation audio compression system was developed by Oscar Bonello, an engineering professor at the University of Buenos Aires.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This broadcast automation system was launched in 1987 under the name Audicom.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] A literature compendium for a large variety of audio coding systems was published in the IEEE's *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* (*JSAC*), in February 1988.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] While there were some papers from before that time, this collection documented an entire variety of finished, working audio coders, nearly all of them using perceptual techniques and some kind of frequency analysis and back-end noiseless coding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Uncompressed video requires a very high data rate.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Although lossless video compression codecs perform at a compression factor of 5 to 12, a typical H.264 lossy compression video has a compression factor between 20 and 200.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards are the DCT and motion compensation (MC).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT video coding (block motion compensation).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Most video codecs are used alongside audio compression techniques to store the separate but complementary data streams as one combined package using so-called *container formats*.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Video data may be represented as a series of still image frames.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Such data usually contains abundant amounts of spatial and temporal redundancy.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Video compression algorithms attempt to reduce redundancy and store information more compactly.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Most video compression formats and codecs exploit both spatial and temporal redundancy (e.g., through difference coding with motion compensation).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Similarities can be encoded by only storing differences between e.g., temporally adjacent frames (inter-frame coding) or spatially adjacent pixels (intra-frame coding).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Inter-frame compression (a temporal delta encoding) (re)uses data from one or more earlier or later frames in a sequence to describe the current frame.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Intra-frame coding, on the other hand, uses only data from within the current frame, effectively being still-image compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The intra-frame video coding formats used in camcorders and video editing employ simpler compression that uses only intra-frame prediction.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This simplifies video editing software, as it prevents a situation in which a compressed frame refers to data that the editor has deleted.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Usually, video compression additionally employs lossy compression techniques like quantization that reduce aspects of the source data that are (more or less) irrelevant to the human visual perception by exploiting perceptual features of human vision.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For example, small differences in color are more difficult to perceive than are changes in brightness.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Compression algorithms can average a color across these similar areas in a manner similar to those used in JPEG image compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] As in all lossy compression, there is a trade-off between video quality and bit rate, cost of processing the compression and decompression, and system requirements.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Highly compressed video may present visible or distracting artifacts.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Other methods other than the prevalent DCT-based transform formats, such as fractal compression, matching pursuit and the use of a discrete wavelet transform (DWT), have been the subject of some research, but are typically not used in practical products.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression is used in still-image coders and video coders without motion compensation.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Interest in fractal compression seems to be waning, due to recent theoretical analysis showing a comparative lack of effectiveness of such methods.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In inter-frame coding, individual frames of a video sequence are compared from one frame to the next, and the video compression codec records the differences to the reference frame.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system can simply issue a short command that copies that part of the previous frame into the next one.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor can emit a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] This longer command still remains much shorter than data generated by intra-frame compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Usually, the encoder will also transmit a residue signal which describes the remaining, more subtle differences to the reference imagery.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Using entropy coding, these residue signals have a more compact representation than the full signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In areas of video with more motion, the compression must encode more data to keep up with the larger number of pixels that are changing.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Commonly, the high-frequency detail of explosions, flames, flocks of animals, and some panning shots will lead to decreases in quality or increases in the variable bitrate.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Many commonly used video compression methods (e.g., those in standards approved by the ITU-T or ISO) share the same basic architecture that dates back to H.261, which was standardized in 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] They mostly rely on the DCT, applied to rectangular blocks of neighboring pixels, and temporal prediction using motion vectors, as well as nowadays also an in-loop filtering step.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the prediction stage, various deduplication and difference-coding techniques are applied that help decorrelate data and describe new data based on already transmitted data.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Then, rectangular blocks of remaining pixel data are transformed to the frequency domain.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the main lossy processing stage, frequency domain data gets quantized in order to reduce information that is irrelevant to human visual perception.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In the last stage, statistical redundancy gets largely eliminated by an entropy coder, which often applies some form of arithmetic coding.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In an additional in-loop filtering stage, various filters can be applied to the reconstructed image signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] By computing these filters also inside the encoding loop, they can help compression because they can be applied to reference material before it gets used in the prediction process and they can be guided using the original signal.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The most popular example are deblocking filters that blur out blocking artifacts from quantization discontinuities at transform block boundaries.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Cherry proposed a run-length encoding bandwidth compression scheme for the transmission of analog television signals.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The DCT, which is fundamental to modern video compression, was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] H.261, which debuted in 1988, commercially introduced the prevalent basic architecture of video compression technology.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It was the first video coding format based on DCT compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] H.261 was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT and Toshiba.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It was also developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] AVC commercially introduced the modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) and context-adaptive variable-length coding (CAVLC) algorithms.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Genetics compression algorithms are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and genetic algorithms adapted to the specific datatype.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published a genetic compression algorithm that does not use a reference genome for compression.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression and is less computationally intensive than the leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] For this, Chanda, Elhaik, and Bader introduced MAF-based encoding (MAFE), which reduces the heterogeneity of the dataset by sorting SNPs by their minor allele frequency, thus homogenizing the dataset.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] Other algorithms developed in 2009 and 2013 (DNAZip and GenomeZip) have compression ratios of up to 1200-fold—allowing 6 billion basepair diploid human genomes to be stored in 2.5 megabytes (relative to a reference genome or averaged over many genomes).
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the total amount of data that is stored on the world's storage devices could be further compressed with existing compression algorithms by a remaining average factor of 4.5:1.
[src:gguf-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the combined technological capacity of the world to store information provides 1,300 exabytes of hardware digits in 2007, but when the corresponding content is optimally compressed, this only represents 295 exabytes of Shannon information.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A **file format** is the way that information is encoded for storage in a computer file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It may describe the encoding at various levels of abstraction including low-level bit and byte layout as well high-level organization such as markup and tabular structure.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A file format may be standardized (which can be proprietary or open) or it can be an *ad hoc* convention.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Some file formats are designed for very particular types of data: PNG files, for example, store bitmapped images using lossless data compression.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Other file formats, however, are designed for storage of several different types of data: the Ogg format can act as a container for different types of multimedia including any combination of audio and video, with or without text (such as subtitles), and metadata.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A text file can contain any stream of characters, including possible control characters, and is encoded in one of various character encoding schemes.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Some file formats, such as HTML, scalable vector graphics, and the source code of computer software are text files with defined syntaxes that allow them to be used for specific purposes.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Some file formats have a published specification describing the format and possibly how to verify the correctness of data in that format.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Such a document is not available for every format (sometimes because the format is considered a trade secret, and sometimes because a document was not authored).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Sometimes, a format is defined *de facto* by the behavior of the program that accesses the file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] If there is no specification available, a developer might reverse engineer the format by inspecting files in that format or acquire the specification for a fee and by signing a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Due to the time and money cost of these approaches, file formats with publicly available specifications tend to be supported by more programs.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Patent law (rather than copyright) can be used to protect the intellectual property inherent in a file format.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Although a patent for a file format is not directly permitted under US law, some formats encode data using a patented algorithm.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, prior to 2004, using compression with the GIF file format required the use of a patented algorithm, and though the patent owner did not initially enforce their patent, they later began collecting royalty fees.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This has resulted in a significant decrease in the use of GIFs, and is partly responsible for the development of the alternative PNG format.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] However, the GIF patent expired in the US in mid-2003, and worldwide in mid-2004.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Both users and applications need to identify a file's format so that the file can be used appropriately.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Generally, the methods for identification vary by operating system, with each approach having its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] One popular method used by many operating systems, including Windows, macOS, CP/M, MS-DOS, VMS, and VM/CMS, is to indicate the format of a file with a suffix of the file name, known as the extension.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, an HTML document is identified by a file name that ends with .html or .htm, and a GIF image by .gif.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] In the now-antiquated FAT file system, file names were limited to eight characters for the base name plus a three-character extension, known as an 8.3 filename.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Due to the prevalence of this naming scheme, many formats still use three-character extensions even though modern systems support longer extensions.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Since there is no standardized list of extensions, more than one format can use the same extension – especially for three-letter extensions since there is a limited number of three-letter combinations.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This situation can confuse both users and applications.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] One implication of indicating the file type with the extension is that the users and applications can be tricked into treating a file as a different format simply by renaming it.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, an HTML file can be treated as plain text by adding (or changing the existing) extension filename.txt.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Although this strategy is useful, it can be confusing to less technical users who accidentally make a file unusable (or "lose" it).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] To try to avoid this scenario, Windows and macOS support hiding the extension.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Hiding the extension, however, can create the appearance of multiple files with the same name in the same folder, which is confusing for people.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, an image may be needed both in .eps format (for publishing) and .png format (for web sites) and one might name them with the same base name (for example, CompanyLogo.eps and CompanyLogo.png).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] With extensions hidden they appear to have the same name: CompanyLogo.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Hiding extensions can also pose a security risk.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, a malicious user could create an executable program with an innocent name such as "Holiday photo.jpg.exe".
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The ".exe" would be hidden and an unsuspecting user would see "Holiday photo.jpg", which would appear to be a JPEG image, usually unable to harm the machine.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] However, the operating system would still see the ".exe" extension and run the program, which would then be able to cause harm to the computer.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The same is true with files with only one extension: as it is not shown to the user, no information about the file can be deduced without explicitly investigating the file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] To further trick users, it is possible to store an icon inside the program, in which case some operating systems' icon assignment for the executable file (.exe) would be overridden with an icon commonly used to represent JPEG images, making the program look like an image.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Extensions can also be spoofed: some Microsoft Word macro viruses create a Word file in template format and save it with a .doc extension.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Since Word generally ignores extensions and looks at the format of the file, these would open as templates, execute, and spread the virus.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This represents a practical problem for Windows systems where extension-hiding is turned on by default.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A file's format may be indicated inside the file itself – either as information intended for this purpose or as identifiable data within the format that can be used for identification even though that is not its intended purpose.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Often intentionally placed information is located at the beginning of a file since this is relatively easy to read from a file both by users and applications.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] When the information at the beginning of the file is a structure that contains other metadata, then the structure is often called a *file header*.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] When the file starts with a relatively small datum that only indicates the format, then it is often called a *magic number*.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The metadata contained in a file header are usually stored at the start of the file, but might be present in other areas too, often including the end, depending on the file format or the type of data contained.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Character-based (text) files usually have character-based headers, whereas binary formats usually have binary headers, although this is not a rule.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Text-based file headers usually take up more space, but being human-readable, they can easily be examined by using simple software such as a text editor or a hexadecimal editor.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] As well as indicating the file format, file headers may contain metadata about the file and its contents.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, most image files store information about image format, size, resolution and color space, and optionally authoring information such as who made the image, when and where it was made, what camera model and photographic settings were used (Exif), and so on.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Such metadata may be used by software reading or interpreting the file during the loading process and afterwards.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] File headers may be used by an operating system to quickly gather information about a file without loading it all into memory, but doing so uses more of a computer's resources than reading directly from the directory information.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For instance, when a graphic file manager has to display the contents of a folder, it must read the headers of many files before it can display the appropriate icons, but these will be located in different places on the storage medium thus taking longer to access.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A folder containing many files with complex metadata such as thumbnail information may require considerable time before it can be displayed.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] If a header is binary hard-coded such that the header itself needs complex interpretation in order to be recognized, especially for metadata content protection's sake, there is a risk that the file format can be misinterpreted.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It may even have been badly written at the source.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This can result in corrupt metadata which, in extremely bad cases, might even render the file unreadable.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A more complex example of file headers are those used for wrapper (or container) file formats.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] One way to incorporate file type metadata is to store a "magic number" inside the file itself.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Originally, this term was used for 2-byte identifiers at the start of files, but since any binary sequence can be regarded as a number, any feature of a file format which uniquely distinguishes it can be used for identification.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] GIF images, for instance, always begin with the ASCII representation of either `GIF87a` or `GIF89a`, depending upon the standard to which they adhere.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Many file types, especially plain-text files, are harder to spot by this method.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] HTML files, for example, might begin with the string `<html>` (which is not case sensitive), or an appropriate document type definition that starts with `<!DOCTYPE html`, or, for XHTML, the XML identifier, which begins with `<?xml`.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The files can also begin with HTML comments, random text, or several empty lines, but still be usable HTML.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The magic number approach offers better guarantees that the format will be identified correctly, and can often determine more precise information about the file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Also, data must be read from the file itself, increasing latency as opposed to metadata stored in the directory.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Where file types do not lend themselves to recognition in this way, the system must fall back to metadata.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] On the other hand, a valid magic number does not guarantee that the file is not corrupt or is of a correct type.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] So-called shebang lines in script files are a special case of magic numbers.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] There, the magic number consists of human-readable text within the file that identifies a specific interpreter and options to be passed to it.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This system was then enhanced with the Amiga standard Datatype recognition system.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Another method was the FourCC method, originating in OSType on Macintosh, later adapted by Interchange File Format (IFF) and derivatives.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A final way of storing the format of a file is to explicitly store information about the format in the file system, rather than within the file itself.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This approach keeps the metadata separate from both the main data and the name, but is also less portable than either filename extensions or "magic numbers", since the format has to be converted from filesystem to filesystem.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] While this is also true to an extent with filename extensions— for instance, for compatibility with MS-DOS's three character limit— most forms of storage have a roughly equivalent definition of a file's data and name, but may have varying or no representation of further metadata.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Note that zip files and other archive files solve the problem of handling metadata.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A utility program collects multiple files together along with metadata about each file and the folders/directories they came from all within one new file (e.g. a zip file with extension .zip).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The new file is also compressed and possibly encrypted, but now is transmissible as a single file across operating systems by FTP transmissions or sent by email as an attachment.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] At the destination, the single file received has to be unzipped by a compatible utility to be useful.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The problems of handling metadata are solved this way using zip files or archive files.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The Mac OS' Hierarchical File System and HFS+ file system, and the Apple File System, store codes for *creator* and *type* as part of the directory entry for each file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These codes could be any 4-byte sequence but were often selected so that the ASCII representation formed a sequence of meaningful characters, such as an abbreviation of the application's name or the developer's initials.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For instance a HyperCard "stack" file has a *creator* of WILD (from Hypercard's previous name, "WildCard") and a *type* of STAK.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The BBEdit text editor has a creator code of `R*ch` referring to its original programmer, Rich Siegel.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The type code specifies the format of the file, while the creator code specifies the default program to open it with when double-clicked by the user.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, the user could have several text files all with the type code of TEXT, but each open in a different program, due to having differing creator codes.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This feature was intended so that, for example, human-readable plain-text files could be opened in a general-purpose text editor, while programming or HTML code files would open in a specialized editor or IDE.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] However, this feature was often the source of user confusion, as which program would launch when the files were double-clicked was often unpredictable.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] RISC OS uses a similar system, consisting of a 12-bit number which can be looked up in a table of descriptions—e.g. the hexadecimal number `FF5` is "aliased" to PoScript, representing a PostScript file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A Uniform Type Identifier (UTI) is a method used in macOS for uniquely identifying "typed" classes of entities, such as file formats.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It was developed by Apple as a replacement for OSType (type & creator codes).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The UTI is a Core Foundation string, which uses a reverse-DNS string.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Some common and standard types use a domain called public (e.g. public.png for a Portable Network Graphics image), while other domains can be used for third-party types (e.g. com.adobe.pdf for Portable Document Format).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] UTIs can be defined within a hierarchical structure, known as a conformance hierarchy.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Thus, public.png conforms to a supertype of public.image, which itself conforms to a supertype of public.data.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A UTI can exist in multiple hierarchies, which provides great flexibility.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] In IBM OS/VS through z/OS, the VSAM catalog (prior to ICF catalogs) and the VSAM Volume Record in the VSAM Volume Data Set (VVDS) (with ICF catalogs) identifies the type of VSAM dataset.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] In IBM OS/360 through z/OS, a format 1 or 7 Data Set Control Block (DSCB) in the Volume Table of Contents (VTOC) identifies the Dataset Organization (DSORG) of the dataset described by it.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The HPFS, FAT12, and FAT16 (but not FAT32) filesystems allow the storage of "extended attributes" with files.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These comprise an arbitrary set of triplets with a name, a coded type for the value, and a value, where the names are unique and values can be up to 64 KB long.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] There are standardized meanings for certain types and names (under OS/2).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] One such is that the ".TYPE" extended attribute is used to determine the file type.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Its value comprises a list of one or more file types associated with the file, each of which is a string, such as "Plain Text" or "HTML document".
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The NTFS filesystem also allows storage of OS/2 extended attributes, as one of the file *forks*, but this feature is merely present to support the OS/2 subsystem (not present in XP), so the Win32 subsystem treats this information as an opaque block of data and does not use it.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Instead, it relies on other file forks to store meta-information in Win32-specific formats.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] OS/2 extended attributes can still be read and written by Win32 programs, but the data must be entirely parsed by applications.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] On Unix and Unix-like systems, the ext2, ext3, ext4, ReiserFS version 3, XFS, JFS, FFS, and HFS+ filesystems allow the storage of extended attributes with files.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These include an arbitrary list of "name=value" strings, where the names are unique and a value can be accessed through its related name.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The PRONOM Persistent Unique Identifier (PUID) is an extensible scheme of persistent, unique, and unambiguous identifiers for file formats, which has been developed by The National Archives of the UK as part of its PRONOM technical registry service.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] PUIDs can be expressed as Uniform Resource Identifiers using the info:pronom/ namespace.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Although not yet widely used outside of the UK government and some digital preservation programs, the PUID scheme does provide greater granularity than most alternative schemes.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] MIME types are widely used in many Internet-related applications, and increasingly elsewhere, although their usage for on-disc type information is rare.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These consist of a standardised system of identifiers (managed by IANA) consisting of a *type* and a *sub-type*, separated by a slash—for instance, text/html or image/gif.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These were originally intended as a way of identifying what type of file was attached to an e-mail, independent of the source and target operating systems.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] MIME types identify files on BeOS, AmigaOS 4.0 and MorphOS, as well as store unique application signatures for application launching.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] In AmigaOS and MorphOS, the Mime type system works in parallel with Amiga specific Datatype system.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] There are problems with the MIME types though; several organizations and people have created their own MIME types without registering them properly with IANA, which makes the use of this standard awkward in some cases.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] File format identifiers are another, not widely used way to identify file formats according to their origin and their file category.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It was created for the Description Explorer suite of software.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It is composed of several digits of the form `NNNNNNNNN-XX-YYYYYYY`.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The first part indicates the organization origin/maintainer (this number represents a value in a company/standards organization database), and the 2 following digits categorize the type of file in hexadecimal.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The final part is composed of the usual filename extension of the file or the international standard number of the file, padded left with zeros.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, the PNG file specification has the FFID of `000000001-31-0015948` where `31` indicates an image file, `0015948` is the standard number and `000000001` indicates the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Another less popular way to identify the file format is to examine the file contents for distinguishable patterns among file types.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The contents of a file are a sequence of bytes and a byte has 256 unique permutations (0–255).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Thus, counting the occurrence of byte patterns that is often referred to as byte frequency distribution gives distinguishable patterns to identify file types.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] There are many content-based file type identification schemes that use a byte frequency distribution to build the representative models for file type and use any statistical and data mining techniques to identify file types.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] There are several types of ways to structure data in a file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The most usual ones are described below.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Earlier file formats used raw data formats that consisted of directly dumping the memory images of one or more structures into the file.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Unless the memory images also have reserved spaces for future extensions, extending and improving this type of structured file is very difficult.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] It also creates files that might be specific to one platform or programming language (for example a structure containing a Pascal string is not recognized as such in C).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] On the other hand, developing tools for reading and writing these types of files is very simple.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The limitations of the unstructured formats led to the development of other types of file formats that could be easily extended and be backward compatible at the same time.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] In this kind of file structure, each piece of data is embedded in a container that somehow identifies the data.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The container's scope can be identified by start- and end-markers of some kind, by an explicit length field somewhere, or by fixed requirements of the file format's definition.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Throughout the 1970s, many programs used formats of this general kind.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] For example, word-processors such as troff, Script, and Scribe, and database export files such as CSV.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Electronic Arts and Commodore-Amiga also used this type of file format in 1985, with their IFF (Interchange File Format) file format.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] A container is sometimes called a *"chunk"*, although "chunk" may also imply that each piece is small, and/or that chunks do not contain other chunks; many formats do not impose those requirements.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The information that identifies a particular "chunk" may be called many different things, often terms including "field name", "identifier", "label", or "tag".
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The identifiers are often human-readable, and classify parts of the data: for example, as a "surname", "address", "rectangle", "font name", etc.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] These are not the same thing as identifiers in the sense of a database key or serial number (although an identifier may well identify its *associated data* as such a key).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] With this type of file structure, tools that do not know certain chunk identifiers simply skip those that they do not understand.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Depending on the actual meaning of the skipped data, this may or may not be useful (CSS explicitly defines such behavior).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This concept has been used again and again by RIFF (Microsoft-IBM equivalent of IFF), PNG, JPEG storage, DER (Distinguished Encoding Rules) encoded streams and files (which were originally described in CCITT X.409:1984 and therefore predate IFF), and Structured Data Exchange Format (SDXF).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] This is another extensible format, that closely resembles a file system (OLE Documents are actual filesystems), where the file is composed of 'directory entries' that contain the location of the data within the file itself as well as its signatures (and in certain cases its type).
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Good examples of these types of file structures are disk images, executables, OLE documents TIFF, libraries.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Some file formats like ODT and DOCX, being PKZIP-based, are both chunked and carry a directory.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The structure of a directory-based file format lends itself to modifications more easily than unstructured or chunk-based formats.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] The nature of this type of format allows users to carefully construct files that causes reader software to do things the authors of the format never intended to happen.
[src:gguf-format/file-format] Directory-based file formats also use values that point at other areas in the file but if some later data value points back at data that was read earlier, it can result in an infinite loop for any reader software that assumes the input file is valid and blindly follows the loop.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:gguf-format/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] A **memory-mapped file** is a segment of virtual memory that has been assigned a direct byte-for-byte correlation with some portion of a file or file-like resource.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] This resource is typically a file that is physically present on disk, but can also be a device, shared memory object, or other resource that an operating system can reference through a file descriptor.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Once present, this correlation between the file and the memory space permits applications to treat the mapped portion as if it were primary memory.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] 1969) implementation of this was the **PMAP** system call on the DEC-20's TOPS-20 operating system, a feature used by Software House's System-1022 database system.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Two decades after the release of TOPS-20's PMAP, Windows NT was given Growable Memory-Mapped Files (GMMF).
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Since "`CreateFileMapping` function requires a size to be passed to it" and altering a file's size is not readily accommodated, a GMMF API was developed.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Use of GMMF requires declaring the maximum to which the file size can grow, but no unused space is wasted.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The benefit of memory mapping a file is increasing I/O performance, especially when used on large files.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For small files, memory-mapped files can result in a waste of slack space as memory maps are always aligned to the page size, which is mostly 4 KiB.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Therefore, a 5 KiB file will allocate 8 KiB and thus 3 KiB are wasted.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Accessing memory mapped files is faster than using direct read and write operations for two reasons.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Firstly, a system call is orders of magnitude slower than a simple change to a program's local memory.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Secondly, in most operating systems the memory region mapped actually *is* the kernel's page cache (file cache), meaning that no copies need to be created in user space.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Certain application-level memory-mapped file operations also perform better than their physical file counterparts.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Applications can access and update data in the file directly and in-place, as opposed to seeking from the start of the file or rewriting the entire edited contents to a temporary location.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Since the memory-mapped file is handled internally in pages, linear file access (as seen, for example, in flat file data storage or configuration files) requires disk access only when a new page boundary is crossed, and can write larger sections of the file to disk in a single operation.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] A possible benefit of memory-mapped files is a "lazy loading", thus using small amounts of RAM even for a very large file.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Trying to load the entire contents of a file that is significantly larger than the amount of memory available can cause severe thrashing as the operating system reads from disk into memory and simultaneously writes pages from memory back to disk.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Memory-mapping may not only bypass the page file completely, but also allow smaller page-sized sections to be loaded as data is being edited, similarly to demand paging used for programs.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The memory mapping process is handled by the virtual memory manager, which is the same subsystem responsible for dealing with the page file.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Memory mapped files are loaded into memory one entire page at a time.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The page size is selected by the operating system for maximum performance.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Since page file management is one of the most critical elements of a virtual memory system, loading page sized sections of a file into physical memory is typically a very highly optimized system function.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Persisted files are associated with a source file on a disk.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The data is saved to the source file on the disk once the last process is finished.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] These memory-mapped files are suitable for working with extremely large source files.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Non-persisted files are not associated with a file on a disk.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] When the last process has finished working with the file, the data is lost.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] These files are suitable for creating shared memory for inter-process communications (IPC).
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The major reason to choose memory mapped file I/O is performance.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The standard I/O approach is costly due to system call overhead and memory copying.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The memory-mapped approach has its cost in minor page faults—when a block of data is loaded in page cache, but is not yet mapped into the process's virtual memory space.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] In some circumstances, memory mapped file I/O can be substantially slower than standard file I/O.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Another drawback of memory-mapped files relates to a given architecture's address space: a file larger than the addressable space can have only portions mapped at a time, complicating reading it.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For example, a 32-bit architecture such as Intel's IA-32 can only directly address 4 GiB or smaller portions of files.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] An even smaller amount of addressable space is available to individual programs—typically in the range of 2 to 3 GiB, depending on the operating system kernel.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] This drawback however is virtually eliminated on modern 64-bit architecture.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] mmap also tends to be less scalable than standard means of file I/O, since many operating systems, including Linux, have a cap on the number of cores handling page faults.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Extremely fast devices, such as modern NVM Express SSDs, are capable of making the overhead a real concern.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] I/O errors on the underlying file (e.g. its removable drive is unplugged or optical media is ejected, disk full when writing, etc.) while accessing its mapped memory are reported to the application as the SIGSEGV/SIGBUS signals on POSIX, and the EXECUTE_IN_PAGE_ERROR structured exception on Windows.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] All code accessing mapped memory must be prepared to handle these errors, which don't normally occur when accessing memory.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Only hardware architectures with an MMU can support memory-mapped files.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] On architectures without an MMU, the operating system can copy the entire file into memory when the request to map it is made, but this is extremely wasteful and slow if only a little bit of the file will be accessed, and can only work for files that will fit in available memory.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Most memory-mapping systems use a technique called demand paging, where the file is loaded into physical memory in subsets (one page each), and only when that page is actually referenced.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] In the specific case of executable files, this permits the OS to selectively load only those portions of a process image that actually need to execute.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Another common use for memory-mapped files is to share memory between multiple processes.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] In modern protected mode operating systems, processes are generally not permitted to access memory space that is allocated for use by another process.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] (A program's attempt to do so causes invalid page faults or segmentation violations.) There are a number of techniques available to safely share memory, and memory-mapped file I/O is one of the most popular.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Two or more applications can simultaneously map a single physical file into memory and access this memory.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For example, the Microsoft Windows operating system provides a mechanism for applications to memory-map a shared segment of the system's page file itself and share data via this section.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Most modern operating systems or runtime environments support some form of memory-mapped file access.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The Microsoft Windows operating systems also support a group of API functions for this purpose, such as CreateFileMapping().
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The Java programming language provides classes and methods to access memory mapped files, such as `FileChannel`.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Furthermore, Java uses memory-mapped approach to load specific classes to decrease the class loading time in JVM - Java Class Data Sharing.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The D programming language supports memory mapped files in its standard library (std.mmfile module)..
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Ruby has a gem (library) called Mmap, which implements memory-mapped file objects.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Rust does not provide any mmap functionality in the standard library but there exists a third-party crate (library) called memmap2.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Since version 1.6, Python has included a mmap module in its Standard Library.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Details of the module vary according to whether the host platform is Windows or Unix-like.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For Perl there are several modules available for memory mapping files on the CPAN, such as Sys::Mmap and File::Map.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] In the Microsoft .NET runtime, P/Invoke can be used to use memory mapped files directly through the Windows API.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Managed access (P/Invoke not necessary) to memory mapped files was introduced in version 4 of the runtime (see Memory-Mapped Files).
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For previous versions, there are third-party libraries which provide managed API's. .NET have the `MemoryMappedFile` class.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] PHP supported memory-mapping techniques in a number of native file access functions such as `file_get_contents()` but has removed this in 5.3 (see revision log).
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] For the R programming language there exists a library on CRAN called bigmemory which uses the Boost library and provides memory-mapped backed arrays directly in R.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The package ff offers memory-mapped vectors, matrices, arrays and data frames.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The J programming language has supported memory-mapped files since at least 2005.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] It includes support for boxed array data, and single datatype files.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] Support can be loaded from 'data/jmf' J's Jdb and JD database engines use memory-mapped files for column stores.
[src:gguf-format/memory-mapped-file] The Julia programming language has support for I/O of memory-mapped binary files through the `Mmap` module within the Standard Library.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:gguf-format/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:gguf-format/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:gguf-format/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
